      Universal proxy
   =20
 =20
The way shareholders vote on corporate questions =E2=80=94=C2=A0routine bor=
ing stuff like electing directors in normal years, exciting stuff like elec=
ting directors in contested proxy fights, or existential stuff like hostile=
 merger proposals =E2=80=94=C2=A0is on their computers. You push a button t=
o vote Yes and a different button to vote No and then you go about your day=
. Even if you care a lot, even if you are the governance specialist at a hu=
ge fund and=C2=A0have spent hours meeting with both sides of a proxy fight,=
 you will vote on computer. You=E2=80=99re not going to schlep to the share=
holder meeting and vote in person. That=E2=80=99s just weird and error-pron=
e and a waste of time; some bored retirees will do this but most profession=
als won=E2=80=99t. Even if you do schlep to the shareholder meeting you wil=
l probably vote on your computer first.But a weird historical quirk of the =
U.S.=C2=A0shareholder voting system is that you=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0vot=
e on your computer before the shareholder meeting. All the voting happens a=
t the shareholder meeting. What happens on your computer is that you vote t=
o =E2=80=9Cgive someone a proxy.=E2=80=9D You nominate someone to vote at t=
he meeting on your behalf, and you tell them how you want to vote, and then=
 they go and vote for you.Ordinarily you do this by computer though technic=
ally, if you are a retail investor with (1) an old-timey commitment to pen =
and paper, (2) a lot of time on your hands but (3) not so much time that yo=
u=E2=80=99re going to go to the shareholder meeting yourself, you can do it=
 on paper. Here is the proxy statement that Exxon Mobil Corp. sent out in i=
ts recent proxy fight. If you scroll to the very end you will find the prox=
y card that was attached to the statement. (It=E2=80=99s called the =E2=80=
=9Cblue proxy card=E2=80=9D; if you got the statement in the mail the card =
was printed on blue paper.) There is a front and a back. The back let=C2=A0=
you check off how you wanted to vote on the proxy fight (the election of di=
rectors) and other stuff that came up at Exxon=E2=80=99s annual meeting. Th=
e front says:The undersigned hereby appoints U.M. Burns, K.C. Frazier, D.R.=
 Oberhelman, S.J. Palmisano, and D.W. Woods, or each or any of them, with p=
ower of substitution, proxies to act and vote shares of common stock of the=
 undersigned at the 2021 annual=C2=A0meeting of shareholders of Exxon Mobil=
 Corporation and at any adjournment or postponement thereof, as indicated, =
upon all matters referred to on the reverse side and described in the proxy=
 statement for the meeting and, at their discretion, upon any other matters=
 that may properly come before the meeting to the extent permitted by Rule =
14a-4(c) under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended.It would be =
funny if those names were random Exxon functionaries but in fact they are b=
oard members; Darren Woods is the chairman of Exxon=E2=80=99s board. Basica=
lly if you signed this card you were letting=C2=A0Exxon=E2=80=99s board vot=
e on your behalf, though on the back you could give them some instructions =
about how you wanted to vote. Meanwhile Exxon=E2=80=99s opponent in the pro=
xy fight, Engine No. 1 LLC, sent its own proxy statement with its own (whit=
e) proxy card, appointing=C2=A0Christopher James, Charles Penner, Eleazer K=
lein and Scott Winter as proxies; two of those are Engine No. 1 executives =
and the other two were its lawyer=C2=A0and proxy solicitor.=C2=A0It=E2=80=
=99s worth looking at the backs of those proxy cards. Exxon=E2=80=99s blue =
proxy allowed shareholders to (1) vote for Exxon=E2=80=99s director nominee=
s or (2)=C2=A0not=C2=A0vote for them. Shareholders had no option to vote fo=
r Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s nominees on Exxon=E2=80=99s card.Engine No. 1=E2=
=80=99s proxy was more complicated. It only proposed four nominees, but the=
re are 12 board seats; Engine No. 1 proposed to vote for eight of Exxon=E2=
=80=99s nominees, vote against four of them, and vote for four of its own d=
irectors. The proxy card allowed you to (1) vote for the eight Exxon nomine=
es plus the four Engine No. 1 nominees or (2) not=C2=A0vote for some of the=
 Engine No. 1 nominees.=C2=A0You had no option to tell Engine No. 1 to go v=
ote for the four Exxon nominees it didn=E2=80=99t want to vote for. (Or not=
 to vote for the ones it did want to vote for!)In practice it was still pos=
sible for some of Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s nominees to win and others to lose=
, and in fact that happened: Some shareholders gave Engine No. 1 their prox=
y but withheld votes from some of its nominees, other shareholders gave Exx=
on their proxy but withheld votes from some of its nominees, and the totals=
 were close enough that three of Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s four nominees won a=
long with one of the contested Exxon nominees. But it is a complicated mech=
anism; you couldn=E2=80=99t just fill out a form saying =E2=80=9Cvote for t=
hree of Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s and one of Exxon=E2=80=99s.=E2=80=9DI have d=
escribed this at some length because it is goofy and antiquated. There are =
literal paper cards that you can fill out giving people instructions on how=
 to vote at an in-person shareholder meeting, but the cards might not allow=
 you to specify your actual preferences. Obviously in a perfect world you w=
ould just log into your computer and it would be like =E2=80=9Cwho do you w=
ant to vote for=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99d pick 12 nominees and vote for th=
em and that would be your vote. There would be no =E2=80=9Cproxies=E2=80=9D=
; you wouldn=E2=80=99t be giving agents instructions on how to vote your sh=
ares at an in-person meeting. You=E2=80=99d just vote online.We are not the=
re yet but last week the U.S. Securities=C2=A0and Exchange Commission did t=
his:The Securities and Exchange Commission today voted to adopt final rules=
 requiring parties in a contested election to use universal proxy cards tha=
t include all director nominees presented for election at a shareholder mee=
ting. The rule changes will give shareholders the ability to vote by proxy =
for their preferred combination of board candidates, similar to voting in p=
erson."These amendments address concerns that shareholders voting by proxy =
cannot vote for a mix of dissident and registrant nominees in an election c=
ontest, as they could if voted in person," said SEC Chair Gary Gensler. "To=
day=E2=80=99s amendments will put these candidates on the same ballot. They=
 will put investors voting in person and by proxy on equal footing. This is=
 an important aspect of shareholder democracy."The final rules will require=
 dissident shareholders and registrants to provide shareholders with a prox=
y card that includes the names of all registrant and dissident nominees.So =
now you can vote for the people you prefer on your computer. It=E2=80=99s a=
 step.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe new rule may make it easier for dissidents to pers=
uade shareholders to vote for a few nominees opposed by management in order=
 to =E2=80=98send a message,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D says Davis Polk & Wardwell L=
LP, which seems to be the basic goal.
