      Jamie v. Elon
   =20
 =20
Here=E2=80=99s a good little statistic:JPMorgan=E2=80=99s investment banker=
s haven=E2=80=99t worked on any Tesla offering or transaction since 2016, a=
ccording to public records. When JPMorgan worked on Tesla=E2=80=99s 2010 in=
itial public offering of stock and several capital-markets transactions in =
the following years, it was usually ranked behind rivals such as Goldman Sa=
chs Group Inc. and Morgan Stanley.JPMorgan has been paid about $15 million =
by Tesla for advice and capital-markets work in the past decade, while Gold=
man has made about $90 million, according to Dealogic.That number is not co=
mprehensive; that=E2=80=99s not all the money that JPMorgan Chase & Co. has=
 made from Tesla Inc. That=E2=80=99s just fees. For instance, as we  discus=
sed last week, JPMorgan sold Tesla some call options and bought back some w=
arrants connected with Tesla=E2=80=99s convertible bond offering in 2014. O=
n trades like that, JPMorgan doesn=E2=80=99t make money from fees; it makes=
 money by charging Tesla more than the fair value of the options it sells (=
and paying less than fair value for the warrants it buys). JPMorgan=E2=80=
=99s edge on a trade like that is not disclosed but my wild guess is that i=
f JPMorgan did a majority of the trade on a $1.38 billion convertible bond =
for Tesla it probably booked an expected profit in the seven digits. But th=
at profit is at-risk; if Tesla=E2=80=99s stock didn=E2=80=99t behave as JPM=
organ expected, or if it didn=E2=80=99t manage its hedge effectively, it co=
uld have made less, or lost money.=C2=A0In the event,=C2=A0as we discussed =
last week, Tesla Chief Executive Officer Elon Musk tweeted that he was goin=
g to take Tesla private (he was not), JPMorgan took the opportunity to invo=
ke a change-of-control adjustment in the warrants and ask Tesla for more sh=
ares, Tesla said no and JPMorgan sued it for $162 million. If JPMorgan wins=
 then it will make 10 times as much from that trade as it has from fees fro=
m Tesla over the past decade.[4]=C2=A0It will make more on that one trade t=
han=C2=A0Goldman, Tesla=E2=80=99s preferred bank, has made from fees from T=
esla over that decade.[5] Doing one corporate equity derivative trade with =
Tesla and then adjusting that trade for a merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, in this=
 case, a pretend merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0is more lucrative than having a deca=
de-long trusted-adviser relationship with one of the world=E2=80=99s larges=
t companies. You can see why JPMorgan decided to burn the relationship and =
sue for the money.=C2=A0Anyway that statistic is from this fun Wall Street =
Journal article about how =E2=80=9CElon Musk and Jamie Dimon don=E2=80=99t =
get along=E2=80=9D:Messrs. Musk and Dimon have tried to patch things up but=
 clashed instead, the people said. JPMorgan decided some time ago that it i=
s better off without Tesla, according to people familiar with the matter. =
=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CWe have provided Tesla multiple opportunities to fulfill =
its contractual obligations, so it is unfortunate that they have forced thi=
s issue into litigation,=E2=80=9D JPMorgan said last week.=E2=80=9CIf JPM d=
oesn=E2=80=99t withdraw their lawsuit, I will give them a one star review o=
n Yelp,=E2=80=9D Mr. Musk said in response to The Wall Street Journal. =E2=
=80=9CThis is my final warning!=E2=80=9DIf you=E2=80=99re the JPMorgan equi=
ty derivatives person with a $162 million invoice for Tesla that they won=
=E2=80=99t pay, I suppose it=E2=80=99s nice that your bank=E2=80=99s relati=
onship with Tesla is =E2=80=9Cour celebrity CEOs dislike each other=E2=80=
=9D rather than, like, =E2=80=9Cwe are the main provider of financing for T=
esla dealerships.=E2=80=9D You can just go sue Tesla and Jamie Dimon will b=
e cheering you on.On the other hand that =E2=80=9CYelp review=E2=80=9D thin=
g is a typical Elon Musk joke, fine, but also true?=C2=A0If you are a big c=
ompany looking to do a convertible bond with a call options overlay, and JP=
Morgan and Goldman Sachs are competing for your business, surely Goldman=E2=
=80=99s bid contains a little note saying =E2=80=9Cand we won=E2=80=99t sue=
 you for $162 million like JPMorgan did to Tesla,=E2=80=9D no? Goldman, Mor=
gan Stanley and Deutsche Bank AG all had similar (though smaller) warrant t=
ransactions with Tesla, and none of them adjusted their warrants and sued f=
or millions of dollars, presumably because their CEOs are not feuding with =
Elon Musk and they have better all-around business relationships.[6] I supp=
ose that=E2=80=99s a selling point for the next deal with the next client.
