      Ken Griffin vs. people on the internet
   =20
 =20
If you are a Reddit-posting shareholder of GameStop Corp. then you probably=
 consider Ken Griffin your enemy. This is based mostly on a misunderstandin=
g of what Griffin=E2=80=99s hedge fund Citadel (and his market maker Citade=
l Securities) does, but that=E2=80=99s not important right now. The importa=
nt thing is that there is an army of retail traders who own GameStop, are o=
nline a lot, and dislike Griffin. I gather there are other popular meme sto=
cks whose investors dislike Griffin too, though the GameStop/Griffin relati=
onship=C2=A0seems particularly intense.An army of cryptocurrency investors =
banded together last week to buy a first edition of the U.S. Constitution. =
On Thursday, they failed. They were outbid by Ken Griffin. On Twitter, this=
 was taken to be very funny. And I guess it is! An army of retail traders b=
anding together to accomplish a shared aim with millions of dollars, defeat=
ed by Ken Griffin=E2=80=99s individual wealth, sure, ha ha ha. Here is the =
Wall Street Journal story about how Griffin outbid the ConstitutionDAO peop=
le:The 53-year old founder and chief executive of Citadel caused a stir Thu=
rsday when he outbid a large group of cryptocurrency investors who had crow=
dfunded more than $40 million earlier in the week in a frenzied attempt to =
win the document, the last surviving first edition in private hands. =E2=80=
=A6Mr. Griffin is an unpopular figure among the wave of individual investor=
s whose influence rose during the pandemic through their use of social medi=
a to drive up =E2=80=9Cmeme stocks=E2=80=9D like AMC Entertainment Holdings=
 Inc. and GameStop Corp. Many such investors suspect that his electronic tr=
ading firm, Citadel Securities, an affiliate of the hedge fund, masterminde=
d the decision by Robinhood Markets Inc. and other brokerages to restrict t=
rading in GameStop Corp. on Jan. 28=E2=80=94a move that ended a wild rally =
in the videogame retailer=E2=80=99s stock and caused losses for many small =
investors. Citadel Securities has denied playing any role in the decision.I=
t does not seem obvious to me that Ken Griffin would be an enemy of the cry=
ptocurrency investors who backed ConstitutionDAO. Griffin has said recently=
 that Citadel Securities does not trade crypto. If you are trading crypto y=
ou are probably not interacting at all with Citadel or Citadel Securities o=
r any other Ken Griffin business, except I guess with his personal hobby of=
 buying rare editions of America=E2=80=99s founding documents.=C2=A0Here is=
 some back story=C2=A0on the DAO; a lot of its leaders are sort of venture-=
capital and crypto-builder types, not retail investors with Robinhood accou=
nts and GameStop shares they bought at $483.I guess the question here is, a=
re all the armies of very online individual traders the same army? Are Doge=
coin and Shiba Inu and Tesla and GameStop and AMC and ConstitutionDAO and e=
verything else allied with each other, complements to each other; does ever=
yone who owns one of them own all of them; are they a complete system of ho=
bbies and personalities? Or are they substitutes for each other; if you=E2=
=80=99re putting your money into ConstitutionDAO is it because you=C2=A0did=
n=E2=80=99t put all your money into GameStop?Today=E2=80=99s financial mark=
ets are weird. Huge amounts of money move around not because it makes any f=
inancial sense but because people enjoy coming together to join some sort o=
f online club. And from the outside you can look at these phenomena and be =
like =E2=80=9Cah, right, GameStop,=E2=80=9D but it=E2=80=99s not always lit=
erally GameStop. Many modern financial phenomena are vaguely explained by =
=E2=80=9Cpeople are willing to put up real money to join an online club,=E2=
=80=9D but the whole point of clubs is that there are=C2=A0different=C2=A0c=
lubs. You join ConstitutionDAO because something in it speaks to something =
in you, or because your particular group of friends are all in that club,=
=C2=A0not =E2=80=94=C2=A0I hope? =E2=80=94=C2=A0because you are an indiscri=
minate club-joiner. You might like GameStop and shiba inus and scarce JPEGs=
 and crowdfunding a copy of the Constitution but at some point=C2=A0how man=
y of these things can you possibly like?=C2=A0At some point there will need=
 to be a more detailed sociological analysis of meme stocks, and meme crypt=
ocurrencies and non-fungible tokens and all the other essentially social th=
ings people are putting their money into these days. It=E2=80=99s fine to b=
e like =E2=80=9Ceveryone buys these shiba inu-themed things because it is a=
 fun social experience=E2=80=9D but=C2=A0why shiba inus? Why GameStop, why =
Bored Apes, why this copy of=C2=A0the Constitution, why anything? Finance h=
as become fashion. In some ways that has made it simpler =E2=80=94=C2=A0you=
 don=E2=80=99t have to worry about discounted cash flow models anymore, tha=
t=E2=80=99s for sure=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but in most ways it has made it mo=
re mysterious.
