<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Universal proxy</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way shareholders vote on corporate=
 questions =E2=80=94=C2=A0routine boring stuff like electing directors in n=
ormal years, exciting stuff like electing directors in contested proxy figh=
ts, or existential stuff like hostile merger proposals =E2=80=94=C2=A0is on=
 their computers. You push a button to vote Yes and a different button to v=
ote No and then you go about your day. Even if you care a lot, even if you =
are the governance specialist at a huge fund and=C2=A0have spent hours meet=
ing with both sides of a proxy fight, you will vote on computer. You=E2=80=
=99re not going to schlep to the shareholder meeting and vote in person. Th=
at=E2=80=99s just weird and error-prone and a waste of time; some bored ret=
irees will do this but most professionals won=E2=80=99t. Even if you do sch=
lep to the shareholder meeting you will probably vote on your computer firs=
t.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a weird historical quirk of the U.S.=
=C2=A0shareholder voting system is that you=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</e=
m>vote on your computer before the shareholder meeting. All the voting happ=
ens at the shareholder meeting. What happens on your computer is that you v=
ote to =E2=80=9Cgive someone a proxy.=E2=80=9D You nominate someone to vote=
 at the meeting on your behalf, and you tell them how you want to vote, and=
 then they go and vote for you.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ordinarily =
you do this by computer though technically, if you are a retail investor wi=
th (1) an old-timey commitment to pen and paper, (2) a lot of time on your =
hands but (3) not so much time that you=E2=80=99re going to go to the share=
holder meeting yourself, you can do it on paper. Here is <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25793453.280654/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2Vj=
Lmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzM0MDg4LzAwMDExOTMxMjUyMTA4MjE0MC9kOTQxNTl=
kZGVmYzE0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5dcb14bb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the proxy state=
ment</a> that Exxon Mobil Corp. sent out in its recent proxy fight. If you =
scroll to the very end you will find the proxy card that was attached to th=
e statement. (It=E2=80=99s called the =E2=80=9Cblue proxy card=E2=80=9D; if=
 you got the statement in the mail the card was printed on blue paper.) The=
re is a front and a back. The back let=C2=A0you check off how you wanted to=
 vote on the proxy fight (the election of directors) and other stuff that c=
ame up at Exxon=E2=80=99s annual meeting. The front says:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The undersigned hereby appoints U.M. Burns, K.C.=
 Frazier, D.R. Oberhelman, S.J. Palmisano, and D.W. Woods, or each or any o=
f them, with power of substitution, proxies to act and vote shares of commo=
n stock of the undersigned at the 2021 annual=C2=A0meeting of shareholders =
of Exxon Mobil Corporation and at any adjournment or postponement thereof, =
as indicated, upon all matters referred to on the reverse side and describe=
d in the proxy statement for the meeting and, at their discretion, upon any=
 other matters that may properly come before the meeting to the extent perm=
itted by Rule 14a-4(c) under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amende=
d.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It would be funny if those =
names were random Exxon functionaries but in fact they are board members; D=
arren Woods is the chairman of Exxon=E2=80=99s board. Basically if you sign=
ed this card you were letting=C2=A0Exxon=E2=80=99s board vote on your behal=
f, though on the back you could give them some instructions about how you w=
anted to vote. Meanwhile Exxon=E2=80=99s opponent in the proxy fight, Engin=
e No. 1 LLC, sent <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
25793453.280654/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzM0MDg=
4LzAwMDA5MDI2NjQyMTAwMTkzMS9wMjEtMDk1N2RlZmMxNGEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBd66cc2cf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">its own proxy statement</a> with its own (white) prox=
y card, appointing=C2=A0Christopher James, Charles Penner, Eleazer Klein an=
d Scott Winter as proxies; two of those are Engine No. 1 executives and the=
 other two were its <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/25793453.280654/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3J6LmNvbS9sYXd5ZXJzL2VsZWF6ZXIta2xlaW4ua=
HRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB16676b34" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">lawyer</a>=C2=A0and <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25793453.280654/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuaW5uaXNmcmVlbWEuY29tLzIwMjEvdGhlLWxpdHRsZS1lbmdpbmUtdGhhdC1jb3VsZ=
C1hbmQtZGlkLWZlYXR1cmluZy1pbm5pc2ZyZWVzLXNjb3R0LXdpbnRlci8/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBc0667815" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">proxy solicitor</a>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s worth looking at the backs of those proxy cards. Ex=
xon=E2=80=99s blue proxy allowed shareholders to (1) vote for Exxon=E2=80=
=99s director nominees or (2)=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>vote for them. Shareho=
lders had no option to vote for Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s nominees on Exxon=E2=
=80=99s card.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s proxy =
was more complicated. It only proposed four nominees, but there are 12 boar=
d seats; Engine No. 1 proposed to vote for eight of Exxon=E2=80=99s nominee=
s, vote against four of them, and vote for four of its own directors. The p=
roxy card allowed you to (1) vote for the eight Exxon nominees plus the fou=
r Engine No. 1 nominees or (2) <em>not=C2=A0</em>vote for some of the Engin=
e No. 1 nominees.=C2=A0You had no option to tell Engine No. 1 to go vote fo=
r the four Exxon nominees it didn=E2=80=99t want to vote for. (Or not to vo=
te for the ones it did want to vote for!)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
n practice it was still possible for some of Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s nominee=
s to win and others to lose, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/25793453.280654/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hp=
dmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMDAwMDAzNDA4OC8wMDAwMDM0MDg4MjEwMDAwMzEveG9tLTIwMjEwNTI=
2Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc28d5166" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">in fact that happened</a=
>: Some shareholders gave Engine No. 1 their proxy but withheld votes from =
some of its nominees, other shareholders gave Exxon their proxy but withhel=
d votes from some of its nominees, and the totals were close enough that th=
ree of Engine No. 1=E2=80=99s four nominees won along with one of the conte=
sted Exxon nominees. But it is a complicated mechanism; you couldn=E2=80=99=
t just fill out a form saying =E2=80=9Cvote for three of Engine No. 1=E2=80=
=99s and one of Exxon=E2=80=99s.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
 have described this at some length because it is goofy and antiquated. The=
re are literal paper cards that you can fill out giving people instructions=
 on how to vote at an in-person shareholder meeting, but the cards might no=
t allow you to specify your actual preferences. Obviously in a perfect worl=
d you would just log into your computer and it would be like =E2=80=9Cwho d=
o you want to vote for=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99d pick 12 nominees and vote=
 for them and that would be your vote. There would be no =E2=80=9Cproxies=
=E2=80=9D; you wouldn=E2=80=99t be giving agents instructions on how to vot=
e your shares at an in-person meeting. You=E2=80=99d just vote online.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We are not there yet but last week the U.S. Sec=
urities=C2=A0and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/25793453.280654/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNz=
LXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0yMzU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea77a455" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">did this=
</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchan=
ge Commission today voted to adopt final rules requiring parties in a conte=
sted election to use universal proxy cards that include all director nomine=
es presented for election at a shareholder meeting. The rule changes will g=
ive shareholders the ability to vote by proxy for their preferred combinati=
on of board candidates, similar to voting in person.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">"These amendments address concerns that shareholders voting by pr=
oxy cannot vote for a mix of dissident and registrant nominees in an electi=
on contest, as they could if voted in person," said SEC Chair Gary Gensler.=
 "Today=E2=80=99s amendments will put these candidates on the same ballot. =
They will put investors voting in person and by proxy on equal footing. Thi=
s is an important aspect of shareholder democracy."</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">The final rules will require dissident shareholders and registrant=
s to provide shareholders with a proxy card that includes the names of all =
registrant and dissident nominees.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">So now you can vote for the people you prefer on your computer. It=E2=
=80=99s a step.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe new rule may make it easier for dissident=
s to persuade shareholders to vote for a few nominees opposed by management=
 in order to =E2=80=98send a message,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25793453.280654/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGF2a=
XNwb2xrLmNvbS9pbnNpZ2h0cy9jbGllbnQtdXBkYXRlL3NlYy1tYW5kYXRlcy11bml2ZXJzYWwt=
cHJveHktY2FyZHMtY29udGVzdGVkLWJvYXJkLWVsZWN0aW9ucw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B2d447b18" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">says Davis Polk &amp; Wardwell LLP</a>, which seems to b=
e the basic goal.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
