StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> dis=
cussed last week</a>, JPMorgan sold Tesla some call options and bought back=
 some warrants connected with Tesla=E2=80=99s convertible bond offering in =
2014. On trades like that, JPMorgan doesn=E2=80=99t make money from fees; i=
t makes money by charging Tesla more than the fair value of the options it =
sells (and paying less than fair value for the warrants it buys). JPMorgan=
=E2=80=99s edge on a trade like that is not disclosed but my wild guess is =
that if JPMorgan did a majority of the trade on a $1.38 billion convertible=
 bond for Tesla it probably booked an expected profit in the seven digits. =
But that profit is at-risk; if Tesla=E2=80=99s stock didn=E2=80=99t behave =
as JPMorgan expected, or if it didn=E2=80=99t manage its hedge effectively,=
 it could have made less, or lost money.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">In the event,=C2=A0as we discussed last week, Tesla Chief Executive Off=
icer Elon Musk tweeted that he was going to take Tesla private (he was not)=
, JPMorgan took the opportunity to invoke a change-of-control adjustment in=
 the warrants and ask Tesla for more shares, Tesla said no and JPMorgan sue=
d it for $162 million. If JPMorgan wins then it will make 10 times as much =
from that trade as it has from fees from Tesla over the past decade.[4]=C2=
=A0It will make more on that one trade than=C2=A0Goldman, Tesla=E2=80=99s p=
referred bank, has made from fees from Tesla over that decade.[5] Doing one=
 corporate equity derivative trade with Tesla and then adjusting that trade=
 for a merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, in this case, a pretend merger =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is more lucrative than having a decade-long trusted-adviser relations=
hip with one of the world=E2=80=99s largest companies. You can see why JPMo=
rgan decided to burn the relationship and sue for the money.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway that statistic is from this <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25793453.280654/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3=
NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9qcG1vcmdhbnMtamFtaWUtZGltb24tYW5kLXRlc2xhcy1lbG9uLW11c=
2stZmV1ZC1iZWhpbmQtdGhlLXNjZW5lcy0xMTYzNzU4NjAwMT9tb2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M2/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCdcadfa78" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">fun Wall Street Journal article</a>=
 about how =E2=80=9CElon Musk and Jamie Dimon don=E2=80=99t get along=E2=80=
=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Messrs. Musk and Dimon hav=
e tried to patch things up but clashed instead, the people said. JPMorgan d=
